{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508510"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:05:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2762"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2762"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.06,0.08,0.56,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113139"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2762"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95166"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"1318"},{"type":"tags","id":"3840"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46675"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113139"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner concerned because she has noticed bleeding after sex with her partner. It started happening about two weeks ago and happens almost every time now. She describes it as small amounts of blood on the sheets and toilet paper if she wipes afterwards. She denies pain, itching or abnormal vaginal discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has been sexually active with one person only, who is her current partner. They use condoms for protection, and she takes the COCP (combined oral contraceptive pill). Her last menstrual period was 2 weeks ago, and she describes it as being normal. She has never had a sexually transmitted infection or been screened for them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no medical conditions or allergies. She is up to date on her vaccinations including the HPV vaccine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important action to take in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer her for an urgent gynaecological assessment","Perform a test for mycoplasma genitalium","Advise her to get her cervical screening test early","Do a cervical co-test (human papilloma virus and liquid-based cytology)","Perform a pregnancy test"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPost coital bleeding is a red flag symptom for cervical cancer and therefore must be excluded utilising an appropriate investigation. Although this malignancy is rare, especially in younger females, it must always be excluded in the case of inter-menstrual and/or post-coital bleeding. Therefore, the most important action in this is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eperform a cervical co-test (human papilloma virus and liquid-based cytology)\u003C/strong\u003E. This test will look for the HPV virus (a known cause of most cervical cancer) and do cytology (for cell changes consistent with cancer).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical screening test\u003C/strong\u003E starts at age 25 for women and is used for asymptomatic screening. It \u003Cstrong\u003Eshould NOT be used when a patient is presenting\u003C/strong\u003E with symptoms, such as in this case as it only consists of HPV serology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA pregnancy test\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate, however, from the history there is no indication that she may be pregnant. Her last period was 2 weeks ago, and she is using contraception with a COCP and condoms. It is likely that it would be done to exclude pregnancy but is not the most important action in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycoplasma genitalium\u003C/strong\u003E is a STI that can cause post-coital bleeding but is rare and not part of the routine screening for STI\u2019s. This could be considered later down the track if no other causes were found but would not be an initial test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe does not require an \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent gynaecological assessment\u003C/strong\u003E as the initial tests such as STI screen and co-test can be done in the GP setting and referral based on these results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA differential for the cause of post-coital bleeding is a sexually transmitted infection such as chlamydia. This female has minimal risk factors for an infection and displays no symptoms. However, she has never been screened and it would be appropriate to perform a STI screening test for chlamydia and gonorrhoea, which can be done at the same time as the cervical swab. Additionally swabbing for candidiasis and bacterial vaginosis may also reveal a potential cause for her post-coital bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical screening testing is for asymptomatic individuals.","Post-coital or inter-menstrual bleeding is a red flag symptom and should be investigated for cervical cancer.","A cervical co-test (HPV and LBC) can be used for symptomatic individuals."],"references":["Australian STI Management Guidelines for us in Primary Care, 2018. Mycoplasma genitalium. The Australian Government Department of Health. Access at: http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/mycoplasma-genitalium#cause.","The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetrics and Gynaecologists, 2018. Investigation of intermenstrual and postcoital bleeding. Access at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/RANZCOG_SITE/media/RANZCOG-MEDIA/Women%27s%20Health/Statement%20and%20guidelines/Clinical%20-%20Gynaecology/Investigation-of-intermenstrual-and-postcoital-bleeding(C-Gyn-6)-March-2018.pdf?ext=.pdf."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95166"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2762"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95166"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T20:31:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T20:32:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2762"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113139"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"cr